"Damineli B.L., Kemeid F.M., Aguiar P.S., John V.M.","Measuring the eco-efficiency of cement use",2010,"Cement and Concrete Composites","32","8",,"555","562",,,10.1016/j.cemconcomp.2010.07.009,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77955715344&partnerID=40&md5=739b9015236e367a06104d72127d84d4","Department of Construction Engineering, Escola Politécnica, University of São Paulo, 05508-900 São Paulo, SP, Brazil","Damineli, B.L., Department of Construction Engineering, Escola Politécnica, University of São Paulo, 05508-900 São Paulo, SP, Brazil; Kemeid, F.M., Department of Construction Engineering, Escola Politécnica, University of São Paulo, 05508-900 São Paulo, SP, Brazil; Aguiar, P.S., Department of Construction Engineering, Escola Politécnica, University of São Paulo, 05508-900 São Paulo, SP, Brazil; John, V.M., Department of Construction Engineering, Escola Politécnica, University of São Paulo, 05508-900 São Paulo, SP, Brazil","At present, the cement industry generates approximately 5% of the world's anthropogenic CO2 emissions. This share is expected to increase since demand for cement based products is forecast to multiply by a factor of 2.5 within the next 40 years and the traditional strategies to mitigate emissions, focused on the production of cement, will not be capable of compensating such growth. Therefore, additional mitigation strategies are needed, including an increase in the efficiency of cement use. This paper proposes indicators for measuring cement use efficiency, presents a benchmark based on literature data and discusses potential gains in efficiency. The binder intensity (bi) index measures the amount of binder (kg m-3) necessary to deliver 1 MPa of mechanical strength, and consequently express the efficiency of using binder materials. The CO2 intensity index (ci) allows estimating the global warming potential of concrete formulations. Research benchmarks show that bi ∼5 kg m-3 MPa-1 are feasible and have already been achieved for concretes &gt;50 MPa. However, concretes with lower compressive strengths have binder intensities varying between 10 and 20 kg m-3 MPa-1. These values can be a result of the minimum cement content established in many standards and reveal a significant potential for performance gains. In addition, combinations of low bi and ci are shown to be feasible. © 2010 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Blended cement; Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Compressive strength; Mixture proportioning; Sustainability","Binder material; Blended cement; Cement content; Cement-based; Eco-efficiency; Global warming potential; Literature data; Mechanical strength; Mitigation strategy; Mixture proportioning; Performance Gain; Sustainability; Use efficiency; Binders; Carbon dioxide; Cement industry; Compressive strength; Concretes; Global warming; Sustainable development; Cements",,,,,,"Bernstein, L., Roy, J., Delhotal, K.C., Harnisch, J., Matsuhashi, R., Price, L., Industry (2007) Climate Change 2007: Mitigation. Contribution of Working Group III to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, pp. 447-496; The cement sustainability initiative (CSI) (2009) Cement Industry Energy and CO2 Performance: Getting the Numbers Right, p. 44. , http://www.wbcsdcement.org, (CSI report); Müller N, H., (2008) A Blueprint for A Climate Friendly Cement Industry. Gland: WWF Lafarge Conservation Partnership, p. 94. , (WWF - Lafarge conservation partnership report); The cement sustainability initiative (CSI) (2007) The Cement Sustainability Initiative, p. 8. , http://www.wbcsdcement.org, (CSI report); Humphreys, K., Mahasenan, M., Substudy 8: Climate change (2002) Toward A Sustainable Cement Industry, p. 34. , (Battelle/WBCSD report); Kjellsen, K.O., Guimaraes, M., Nilsson, A., (2005) The CO2 Balance of Concrete in A Life Cycle Perspective. Norway, , (Nordic innovation centre report ISBN: 87-7756-758-7); Haselbach, L., Potential for carbon dioxide absorption in concrete (20